    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_458989864" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/458989864" />
    <a title="Lainey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1047767-lainey"><img alt="Lainey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1341070724p2/1047767.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/458989864?book_show_action=true">Nov 18, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lainey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lainey" href="/user/show/1047767-lainey">Lainey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer458989864" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9038185237646337130">I was just so ready for this to be the book that rises above the average quality (for me) of the first two because things are finally moving forward and Raisa is actively fighting to claim her throne...but I just can&apos;t...things still bother me about this series. <br/><br/>My biggest gripe is why the lack of fully realized female characters??? Just because Raisa is one of the two protagonists in this book doesn&apos;t mean it is alright to basically dismiss the other girls in the novel as trivial, frilly, silly</span>
  <span id="freeText9038185237646337130" style="display:none">I was just so ready for this to be the book that rises above the average quality (for me) of the first two because things are finally moving forward and Raisa is actively fighting to claim her throne...but I just can't...things still bother me about this series. <br /><br />My biggest gripe is why the lack of fully realized female characters??? Just because Raisa is one of the two protagonists in this book doesn't mean it is alright to basically dismiss the other girls in the novel as trivial, frilly, silly, etc. <br /><br />Let us run down the list of female characters of Raisa's age and how they are portrayed: <br />(1) Mellony - "frilly and lightweight" as per Amon's assessment. We're supposed to think she's silly for falling for Micah when we know Micah is only after the throne and is really in love with Raisa. <br /><br />(2) Cat Tyburn - so close to a great female character but is demoted to Raisa's maid and basically gets ordered around by Han. <br /><br />(3) Fiona Bayar - smart and ambitious and is probably up to something nefarious (we don't know yet) but still powerless and flirts with Han a lot when we know he's also in love with Raisa. <br /><br />(4) Night Bird - capable warrior but still in love with Nightwalker who is also in love with Raisa (sensing a pattern here?). <br /><br />(5) Annamaya Dubai - she doesn't even get a single line and is now doomed to marry Amon WHO IS ALSO IN LOVE WITH RAISA (just stop it already!).<br /><br />(6) Melissa Hakkam - she counts even though she's basically only in the story so she can be portrayed as being flirty and silly and so not "what a strong woman should be".<br /><br />(7) Talia - yes, she's here and she's still great but her only substantial scene is when she gets severely injured defending Raisa.<br /><br />This whole issue really gets to me because while this series portrays a great friendship between Dancer and Han, why can't the author do the same for female friendships? Why can't we have a female character who Raisa treats and respects as her equal (not socially of course because she's the queen but you know, personally)? Instead we get other girls who either work for her or who she sees as silly butterflies and therefore not worth her time. Just really, how hard is it to write about supportive loving female friendships? <br /><br />And oh yes, there was a scene where Raisa complains that there aren't more women in her council. That was totally great at first but then nothing comes from it. Maybe it gets addressed in the next book but I'm beginning to think that line was thrown there "to cover the bases" without any intention of following through on it.<br /><br />And another thing, why must strong women always be portrayed as warrior women who can fight with swords and arrows? Why is embroidery or art seen as trivial pursuits suitable only for those with nothing better to do with their lives? Someone's character should not be judged on whether they like shoes and silks as opposed to swords and daggers. Liking pretty things like gowns does not mean someone is shallow and trivial, it just signifies an appreciation of beauty.<br /><br />I probably need to stop reading books about princesses for a while.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9038185237646337130" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

